      	<div source="bib:Hultzsch1902-1903_01" type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
<p>In the twenty-fourth year <supplied reason="subaudible">of the reign</supplied> of king Vijaya-Narasiṃhavikramavarman, Cēḻikar, the servant of Skanda-Bāṇādhirāja, fell, having seized <supplied reason="subaudible">back</supplied> the cattle that had been seized by Daḍiya, Bāṇarāja and Mahendravikrama. Let the Kaṉṉāḍakas <supplied reason="explanation">(i.e. the Kanarese people)</supplied> look after this <supplied reason="subaudible">stone</supplied>! [Those who] injure it [shall incur the five great sins].</p><!--Update!-->
      	</div>
         <div type="commentary">
         	<p>Hultzsch: "bears the representation of a warrior riding on a horse at full gallop".</p><!--Update-->
         	<p>Hultzsch: "reign of the (Gaṅga-Pallava) king Vijaya-Narasiṃhavikramavarman".</p><!--Update-->
         	<p>Hultzsch: "The infinitive kâṇga is used in a similar manner in l. 105 of the Kaśākuḍi plates; SII 2, p. 351."</p><!--Update-->
         	<p>Parallel for the formula "[Those who] injure it [shall incur the five great sins]"?</p><!--Update-->
         </div>
      	
